    In Primitive.bind, canonicalize first before calling typeof and fuse the loops that compute them.

    If we canonicalize first, then values largely have an .aval property, and typeof becomes nothing more than simply computing .aval most of the time, which is cheap. If we call typeof first, then canonicalize_value needs to repeat most of the work of inspecting each Python object.

    Further, we can avoid several tuple and iterator allocations if we simply fuse the loops that compute typeof, canonicalize_value, and check for escaped tracers. This doesn't even make the code any longer!

